spec: as3166
version: ">=3.9"
backend: python_module(asyncio)

docs: https://docs.python.org/3/library/asyncio.html

provenance:
  derived_from:
    - "https://docs.python.org/3/library/asyncio.html"
    - "Test vectors verified with Python 3.14.4 on macOS/Darwin 25.4.0, 2026-04-13"
  not_derived_from:
    - "CPython source code"
    - "any proprietary source"
  notes:
    - "Wave 658 (as3166): __add__, __sub__, __mul__ dict-presence for asyncio types."
    - "All values verified with Python 3.14.4 on macOS/Darwin 25.4.0, 2026-04-13."
    - "Classes covered: asyncio.Task, asyncio.Future, asyncio.Queue, asyncio.Event, asyncio.Semaphore, asyncio.Lock, asyncio.Condition, asyncio.BoundedSemaphore, asyncio.Handle, asyncio.TimerHandle, asyncio.Timeout, asyncio.TaskGroup, asyncio.StreamReader, asyncio.StreamWriter."
    - "Key finding (__add__): all 14 asyncio classes return false for __add__. asyncio types are concurrency primitives — none define addition or concatenation in their own __dict__. asyncio.Queue does not support queue + queue concatenation; items are inserted via put() and consumed via get(). asyncio.StreamReader/StreamWriter are byte-stream objects: they do not implement + as concatenation. asyncio.Semaphore/Lock/Condition/BoundedSemaphore are synchronization guards with no arithmetic semantics whatsoever."
    - "Key finding (__sub__): all 14 asyncio classes return false for __sub__. Subtraction is not defined for any asyncio type. asyncio.Semaphore tracks a counter internally, but incrementing/decrementing that counter is handled by acquire()/release() — not by Python's - operator. asyncio.TaskGroup manages a dynamic set of tasks via create_task(), but set difference is not part of its API."
    - "Key finding (__mul__): all 14 asyncio classes return false for __mul__. Multiplication (repetition) is not defined for any asyncio type. asyncio.Queue does not support queue * n replication. asyncio.Handle/TimerHandle manage callbacks; repetition is semantically undefined for callback handles. asyncio.Timeout/TaskGroup are async context managers with no multiplicative semantics."
    - "This is the fifth consecutive all-false wave for all 14 asyncio subjects (waves 654–657 were also all-false). The asyncio library is a pure concurrency API: its types communicate through await, async with, and explicit method calls — never through Python's arithmetic data model. asyncio.Queue is notable: despite being a FIFO data structure, it defines none of the arithmetic dunders — not __add__ (concatenation), __sub__ (difference), nor __mul__ (repetition)."
    - "Cross-wave summary for asyncio subjects:"
    - "  Wave 652 (as3076): __get__ — Task/Future/Queue/Handle true; others false."
    - "  Wave 653 (as3091): __hash__/__eq__/__bool__ — selected true."
    - "  Wave 654 (as3106): __lt__/__le__/__gt__ — TimerHandle true; others false."
    - "  Wave 655 (as3121): __ge__ — TimerHandle true; __repr__ — 12 classes true."
    - "  Wave 656 (as3136): __call__/__len__/__getitem__ — all false for all 14."
    - "  Wave 657 (as3151): __setitem__/__delitem__/__contains__ — all false for all 14."
    - "  Wave 658 (as3166): __add__/__sub__/__mul__ — all false for all 14."
  created_at: "2026-04-13"

error_model: python_exceptions

# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# __add__ dict-presence — operator.contains(Cls.__dict__, '__add__')
#
# All 14 asyncio classes return false for __add__.
# asyncio types are concurrency primitives, not sequences or numeric types.
# asyncio.Queue does not define + for queue concatenation; items are inserted
#   via put()/put_nowait() and consumed via get()/get_nowait().
# asyncio.StreamReader/StreamWriter handle byte streams but do not define
#   __add__ for stream concatenation — buffering is internal, not additive.
# asyncio.Semaphore/Lock/Condition/BoundedSemaphore: synchronization objects
#   with no collection or arithmetic interface of any kind.
# asyncio.Handle/TimerHandle: callback management objects; no addition.
# asyncio.Timeout/TaskGroup: async context manager objects; no addition.
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

