# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# combined — __add__, __sub__, __mul__ across all 14 asyncio subjects
#
# Covers the full matrix: 14 classes x 3 methods = 42 rows.
# __add__: false for all 14 — no concatenation or addition defined.
# __sub__: false for all 14 — no subtraction or difference defined.
# __mul__: false for all 14 — no multiplication or repetition defined.
# All 42 values are false.
# This is the fifth consecutive all-false wave for all 14 asyncio subjects.
# The asyncio library is designed as a pure concurrency API: its types interact
# exclusively through async/await, context-manager protocols, and explicit method
# calls. The arithmetic data model (__add__, __sub__, __mul__) is entirely absent.
# asyncio.Queue is the most notable negative: despite being a FIFO data
# structure, it defines none of the arithmetic dunders. Queues grow via put()
# and shrink via get() — no operator overloading of any kind is used.
# asyncio.Semaphore is the second notable case: a counter-based resource guard
# whose internal count changes only through acquire()/release() — never via
# arithmetic operators.
# Cross-wave summary for asyncio subjects:
#   Wave 652 (as3076): __get__ — Task/Future/Queue/Handle true; others false.
#   Wave 653 (as3091): __hash__/__eq__/__bool__ — selected true.
#   Wave 654 (as3106): __lt__/__le__/__gt__ — TimerHandle true; others false.
#   Wave 655 (as3121): __ge__ — TimerHandle true; __repr__ — 12 classes true.
#   Wave 656 (as3136): __call__/__len__/__getitem__ — all false for all 14.
#   Wave 657 (as3151): __setitem__/__delitem__/__contains__ — all false for all 14.
#   Wave 658 (as3166): __add__/__sub__/__mul__ — all false for all 14.
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

